00:00:22.300 --> 00:00:28.900
OK, so yesterday we learned about equations of planes

00:00:29.860 --> 00:00:32.740
and how to think of free-by-free linear systems

00:00:33.500 --> 00:00:35.720
in terms of intersections of planes

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:39.020
and how to think about them geometrically.

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:43.060
And that in particular led us to see in which cases,

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:47.300
actually, we don't have a unique solution to the system.

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:50.500
But maybe we have no solutions or infinitely many solutions

00:00:51.260 --> 00:00:54.020
because maybe the line of intersection of two of the planes

00:00:54.020 --> 00:00:56.920
happens to be parallel to the other plane.

00:00:57.640 --> 00:01:03.680
So today, well, we'll start by looking

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:04.780
at equations of lines.

00:01:09.700 --> 00:01:14.900
And so in a way, it seems like something

00:01:14.900 --> 00:01:22.720
that we've already seen last time because we have seen that

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:30.760
we can think of a line as the intersection of two planes.

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:36.500
And we know what equations of planes look like.

00:01:38.200 --> 00:01:41.440
So we could describe a line by two equations

00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:44.980
telling us about the two planes that intersect on the line.

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:47.420
That's not the most convenient way

00:01:47.420 --> 00:01:49.040
to think about a line, usually, though.

00:01:50.420 --> 00:01:52.560
Because when you have these two equations,

00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:53.600
how do you solve them?

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:56.320
Well, you can, but takes a bit of effort.

00:01:57.280 --> 00:02:00.580
So instead, there's another representation of a line.

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:10.460
So if you have a line in space, well, you can imagine maybe

00:02:10.460 --> 00:02:13.780
that you have a point on it and that point is moving in time.

00:02:14.500 --> 00:02:18.560
And the line is the trajectory of a point as time varies.

00:02:19.400 --> 00:02:27.780
So think of a line as the trajectory of a moving point.

00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:38.280
And so when we think of the trajectory of a moving point,

00:02:38.460 --> 00:02:40.760
that's called a parametric equation.

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:53.800
So we're going to learn about parametric equations of lines.

00:03:02.280 --> 00:03:09.340
So let's say, for example, that we are looking at the line

00:03:12.180 --> 00:03:14.960
for, so to specify a line in space,

00:03:15.840 --> 00:03:18.740
I can do that by giving you two points on the line,

00:03:18.980 --> 00:03:21.940
or by giving you a point and a vector parallel to the line,

00:03:22.120 --> 00:03:22.600
for example.

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:30.180
So let's say I give you two points on the line minus 1, 2, 2.

00:03:31.180 --> 00:03:35.580
And the other point will be, let's say, 1, 3, negative 1.

00:03:40.400 --> 00:03:42.980
So it's pretty good because we have two points in that line.

00:03:43.620 --> 00:03:45.340
Now, how do we find all the other points?

00:03:46.060 --> 00:03:48.080
Well, there are other points in between these guys,

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:49.300
and also on either side.

00:03:50.700 --> 00:03:54.180
Let's imagine that we have a point that's moving on the line.

00:03:56.200 --> 00:04:00.580
And at times 0, it's here at Q0.

00:04:01.840 --> 00:04:04.720
And in a unit time, I'm not telling you what the unit is.

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:07.100
It could be a second, it could be an hour, it could be a year.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:12.140
At t equals 1, it's going to be at Q1.

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:13.500
And it moves at constant speed.

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:17.400
So maybe at time 1 half, it's going to be here, time 2,

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:18.200
it will be over there.

00:04:18.960 --> 00:04:21.160
And in fact, that point didn't start here.

00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:23.340
Maybe it's always been moving on the line.

00:04:23.820 --> 00:04:25.460
At times minus 2, it was down there.

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:35.220
So let's say Q of t is a moving point.

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:47.520
And at t equals 0, it's at Q0.

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:52.480
And let's say that it moves.

00:04:53.520 --> 00:04:55.860
Well, we could make it move in any way we want,

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:57.780
but probably the easiest to find.

00:04:57.940 --> 00:04:59.580
So our goal is going to find formulas

00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:03.080
for the position of this moving point in terms of t.

00:05:04.180 --> 00:05:07.260
And we'll use that to say, well, any point on the line

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:12.240
is of this form where you have to plug in the correct value of t

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:14.960
depending on when it's hit by the moving point.

00:05:15.860 --> 00:05:19.720
So perhaps it's easiest to do it if we make it move

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:20.720
at constant speed.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.000
And the line, and that speed is chosen so that at time 1,

00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:35.940
it's at Q1.

00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:52.480
So the question we want to answer is what is the position

00:05:54.620 --> 00:06:00.200
at a time t, so the point Q of t?

00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:06.580
Well, to answer that, we have an easy observation,

00:06:06.980 --> 00:06:10.600
which is that the vector from Q0 to Q of t

00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:14.940
is proportional to the vector from Q0 to Q1.

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:20.880
And what's the proportionality factor here?

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:20.940
Yeah.

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:26.580
Yeah, it's exactly t.

00:06:27.500 --> 00:06:33.340
At time 1, Q0, Q is exactly the same.

00:06:33.720 --> 00:06:35.300
Maybe I should run over a picture again.

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:36.800
I have Q0.

00:06:37.540 --> 00:06:38.240
I have Q1.

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:49.700
And after time t, I'm here at Q of t

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:53.100
where this vector from Q0 to Q of t

00:06:57.020 --> 00:07:01.620
is actually going to be t times the vector Q0, Q1.

00:07:03.800 --> 00:07:06.100
So when t increases, it gets longer and longer.

00:07:10.980 --> 00:07:13.100
So does everybody see this now?

00:07:13.540 --> 00:07:14.840
Is that OK?

00:07:15.280 --> 00:07:16.340
Any questions about that?

00:07:19.700 --> 00:07:20.100
Yes?

00:07:20.580 --> 00:07:22.600
The blue is pretty bad.

00:07:23.340 --> 00:07:25.700
OK, so I will try to avoid using blue.

00:07:25.860 --> 00:07:28.020
Thanks for that's fine.

00:07:29.080 --> 00:07:32.940
So OK, I will not use blue anymore.

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:43.480
OK, well, for this time, let me just make everything

00:07:43.480 --> 00:07:45.400
white for now.

00:07:45.840 --> 00:07:48.860
This is vector from Q0 to Q of t.

00:07:48.860 --> 00:07:51.340
This is the point Q of t.

00:07:53.020 --> 00:07:54.540
Is it kind of visible now?

00:07:54.900 --> 00:07:54.920
Yes.

00:07:55.080 --> 00:07:55.320
OK.

00:07:57.440 --> 00:08:00.560
Thanks for pointing it out.

00:08:00.740 --> 00:08:02.240
I will switch to brighter colors.

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:10.600
So OK, so apart from that, I claim now we can find a position

00:08:10.600 --> 00:08:11.440
of this moving point.

00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:16.000
Because, well, this vector is Q0, Q1.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.660
We can find from the coordinates of Q0 and Q1.

00:08:19.380 --> 00:08:23.220
So we just subtract the coordinates of Q0 from those of Q1.

00:08:23.560 --> 00:08:27.960
We'll get that vector Q0, Q1 is 2, 1, minus 3.

00:08:32.980 --> 00:08:43.580
So if I look at it, well, so let's call x of t y of t

00:08:44.940 --> 00:08:48.820
and z of t the coordinates of the point that's moving

00:08:48.820 --> 00:08:56.220
on the line, then we get x of t minus, well, actually,

00:08:56.280 --> 00:09:00.100
plus 1 equals t times 2.

00:09:02.220 --> 00:09:06.940
I'm writing the components of vector Q0, Q of t.

00:09:08.260 --> 00:09:11.460
And here I'm writing t times Q0, Q1.

00:09:13.580 --> 00:09:25.720
y of t minus 2 equals t and z of t minus 2 equals minus 3t.

00:09:26.140 --> 00:09:30.300
So in other terms, the more familiar way

00:09:30.300 --> 00:09:33.300
that we'll use to write these equations,

00:09:34.620 --> 00:09:40.880
let me do it that way instead, minus 1 plus 2t, y of t

00:09:41.480 --> 00:09:49.600
equals 2 plus t, z of t equals 2 minus 3t.

00:09:50.180 --> 00:09:56.100
And if you prefer, I can just say Q of t is Q0 plus t times

00:09:56.100 --> 00:09:57.560
the vector Q0, Q1.

00:10:03.080 --> 00:10:05.880
So that's our first parametric equation

00:10:05.880 --> 00:10:07.560
of a line in this class.

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:10.500
And I hope you see it's not extremely hard.

00:10:10.740 --> 00:10:13.060
In fact, so parametric equations of lines

00:10:13.060 --> 00:10:14.360
always look like that.

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:19.440
x, y, and t are functions of t that are of a form a constant,

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:21.180
plus a constant times t.

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:25.740
The coefficients of t tell us about a vector along the line.

00:10:26.500 --> 00:10:32.320
Here we have a vector Q0, Q1, which is 2, 1, negative 3.

00:10:33.300 --> 00:10:36.780
And the constant terms tell us about where we are at t equals 0.

00:10:36.780 --> 00:10:38.740
If I play t equals 0, if this guy's going away,

00:10:39.260 --> 00:10:41.800
and get minus 1, 2, 2, that's my starting point.

00:10:54.940 --> 00:10:56.380
Any questions about that?

00:11:01.480 --> 00:11:03.560
OK, so let's see.

00:11:04.280 --> 00:11:07.060
Now what we can do with this parametric equations.

00:11:11.420 --> 00:11:24.020
So one application is to think about the relative position

00:11:24.020 --> 00:11:26.520
of a line and a plane with respect to each other.

00:11:36.220 --> 00:11:39.780
So let's say that we take still the same line of VAR.

00:11:40.860 --> 00:11:50.600
And let's consider the plane with equation x plus 2y plus 4z

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:51.800
equals 7.

00:11:52.800 --> 00:11:53.980
So I'm giving you this plane.

00:11:54.960 --> 00:11:56.720
And the questions that we're going to ask ourselves

00:11:58.120 --> 00:12:00.260
well, does the line intersect the plane?

00:12:00.420 --> 00:12:01.860
And where does it intersect the plane?

00:12:23.700 --> 00:12:28.780
So let's start with first pre-linear question.

00:12:28.780 --> 00:12:30.200
But maybe we should try to understand.

00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:33.160
We have this point, we have this plane,

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.040
and we have this point Q0 and Q1.

00:12:36.340 --> 00:12:38.580
I'm going to draw them in completely random places.

00:12:39.680 --> 00:12:42.860
Well, our Q0 and Q1 on the same side of a plane

00:12:42.860 --> 00:12:46.840
or on different sides, on opposite sides of a plane.

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:50.080
Or could it be that maybe one of the points is in the plane?

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:55.800
So I think I'm going to let you vote on that.

00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:03.860
So is that readable?

00:13:04.060 --> 00:13:04.680
Is it too small?

00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:09.300
OK, so anyway, the question says relative to the plane

00:13:09.300 --> 00:13:15.040
x plus 2y plus 4z equals 7, this points Q0 and Q1

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:18.220
are they on the same side, on opposite sides,

00:13:18.420 --> 00:13:19.340
is one of them on the plane.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:20.940
We can't decide.

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:30.340
OK, should be better.

00:13:34.540 --> 00:13:37.100
So I see relatively few answers.

00:13:43.220 --> 00:13:44.800
OK, it looks like also a lot of you

00:13:44.800 --> 00:13:46.420
have forgotten their cards.

